<h1>
  coi
  <small class="translation">Hello!</small>
</h1>
<div class="red">
  <h2>
    <b>Lojban</b> is a <b>constructed</b>, <b>syntactically unambiguous</b> human language created to reflect the principles of <b>logic</b>.
  </h2>
  <p>
    Lojban is <b>phonetically unambiguous</b>, meaning that every sound corresponds to a single letter. Any lojban statement can be written using only the twenty-four characters of the lojban alphabet.
  </p>
  <p>The Lojban alphabet is like English, with a few rules and exceptions.</p>
  <div class="examples">
    <div class="line">
      <b>a</b> as in palm,
      <b>e</b> as in get,
      <b>i</b> as in machine,
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <b>o</b> as in more,
      <b>u</b> as in tube,
      <b>y</b> like the u in fun,
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <b>c</b> like the sh in shop,
      <b>g</b> as in gum,
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <b>j</b> like the s in treasure,
      <b>x</b> like the ch in Bach,
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <b>'</b> as a short h sound,
      and <b>.</b> as a short pause.
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>Lojban is <b>lexically unambiguous</b>, meaning that each word has a distinct meaning, spelling and pronunciation. Lojban has no synonyms, homographs, or homophones.</p>
  <div class="examples">
    <p>
      <span class="example">👍</span>
      drani
      <small class="translation">right</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="example">📐</span>
      kurfa
      <small class="translation">right</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="example">➡️</span>
      pritu
      <small class="translation">right</small>
    </p>
  </div>
  <p>
    Lojban is <b>syntactically unambiguous</b>, meaning that any sentence can be interpreted only one way. Lojban relies on scope and word order to determine the relation between words.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <div class="line">
      <p>
      mi klama lo banxa ki'u lo nu carvi kei na ku
      <small class="translation">I didn't go to the bank because it was raining.</small>
      <small class="translation">It was raining, and because of that I didn't go to the bank.</small>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        mi na klama lo banxa ki'u lo nu carvi
        <small class="translation">I didn't go to the bank because it was raining.</small>
        <small class="translation">It's not true that because it was raining I went to the bank</small>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>
  Lojban allows for <b>semantic ambiguity</b>, which means individual words may refer to different things. Lojban pronouns have no default <b>case</b>, <b>animacy</b>, or <b>gender</b>.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        <span class="example">👆</span>
        mi
        <small class="translation">I</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">🙋</span>
        mi
        <small class="translation">me</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">👪</span>
        mi
        <small class="translation">us</small>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        <span class="example">👩</span>
        ta
        <small class="translation">her</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">👨</span>
        ta
        <small class="translation">him</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">📺</span>
        ta
        <small class="translation">it</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">👦👧</span>
        ta
        <small class="translation">they</small>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>
  Neither do they have default <b>number</b> or <b>tense</b>.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        <span class="example">
          <%= image_tag("willjump.jpg", size: "25x50") %>
        </span>
        plipe
        <small class="translation">jump</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">
          <%= image_tag("jumping.jpg", size: "25x50") %>
        </span>
        plipe
        <small class="translation">jump</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">
          <%= image_tag("jumped.jpg", size: "25x50") %>
        </span>
        plipe
        <small class="translation">jump</small>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        <span class="example">🐒</span>
        smani
        <small class="translation">monkey</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">🐒🐒🐒</span>
        smani
        <small class="translation">monkey</small>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>
    However, speakers can express specificity if they wish.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        <span class="example">
          <%= image_tag("willjump.jpg", size: "25x50") %>
        </span>
        ba plipe
        <small class="translation">will jump</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">
          <%= image_tag("jumping.jpg", size: "25x50") %>
        </span>
        ca plipe
        <small class="translation">jumping</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">
          <%= image_tag("jumped.jpg", size: "25x50") %>
        </span>
        pu plipe
        <small class="translation">jumped</small>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        <span class="example">🐒</span>
        pa smani
        <small class="translation">a monkey</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <span class="example">🐒🐒🐒</span>
        su'ore smani
        <small class="translation">monkeys</small>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>
    Lojban was created to test the idea that the language we use limits our ability to think. Instead of simple <em>and</em> and <em>or</em>, lojban uses concepts from formal logic.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <p>
      <span class="example">
        <%= image_tag("a.png", size: "60x50") %>
      </span>
      la .alis. <b>.a</b> la .bob. stali
      <small class="translation">Alice and/or Bob stay.</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="example">
        <%= image_tag("e.png", size: "60x50") %>
      </span>
      la .alis. <b>.e</b> la .bob. stali
      <small class="translation">Alice and Bob both stay.</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="example">
        <%= image_tag("o.png", size: "60x50") %>
      </span>
      la .alis. <b>.o</b> la .bob. stali
      <small class="translation">Alice stays if and only if Bob does.</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="example">
        <%= image_tag("u.png", size: "60x50") %>
      </span>
      la .alis. <b>.u</b> la .bob. stali
      <small class="translation">Alice stay whether or not Bob does.</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="example">
        <%= image_tag("onai.png", size: "60x50") %>
      </span>
      la .alis. <b>.onai</b> la .bob. stali
      <small class="translation">Alice or Bob stay, but not both.</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      <span class="example">
        <%= image_tag("na-a.png", size: "60x50") %>
      </span>
      la .alis. <b>na.a</b> la .bob. stali
      <small class="translation">Alice may stay if Bob does.</small>
    </p>
  </div>
</div>
<div class="blue">
  <p>
    Lojban has 1300 root words which take phonemes from the six most commonly spoken languages in the world, as to be as easy to learn for the greatest number of people.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <p>
      <span class="example">tavla</span>
      <small>From Chinese</small> <b>tá</b>n,
      <small>Spanish</small> h<b>a</b>b<b>l</b>ar,
      <small>English</small> <b>ta</b>lk,
      <small>Hindi</small> b<b>a</b>ka<b>vā</b>da,
      <small>Russian</small> g<b>ovo</b>ritʹ
      <small>and Arabic</small> k<b>ala</b>m
    </p>
  </div>
  <p>
    This also makes Lojban a strong candidate for an international auxiliary language, since it's more culturally neutral than Esperanto.
  </p>
  <p>
    Root words can be used together to express more specific concepts.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        cliva
        <small class="translation">leave</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        zifre
        <small class="translation">free</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        cliva zifre
        <small class="translation">free to leave</small>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>
    They can be combined to expand the Lojban vocabulary.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        mi caucni do
        <small class="translation">I miss you.</small>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        <b>claxu</b>
        <small class="translation">lacking</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>cinmo</b>
        <small class="translation">emotion</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        →
      </p>
      <p>
        caucni
        <small class="translation">emotion of lacking</small>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>
    Spoken Lojban uses penultimate emphesis for <b>self-segmentation</b>, meaning that the spaces between words are made clear. There's no confusion between words like <em>ahead</em> and <em>a head</em>.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        lo jbo<b>pre</b>nu
        <small class="translation">the people of lojban</small>
      </p>
      <p>
        <b>lo</b>jbo <b>pre</b>nu
        <small class="translation">people of lojban</small>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>
  Instead of nouns and verbs, Lojban sentences are constructed of an <b>argument</b> and it's <b>predicates</b>. Lojban uses word order instead of prepositions to determine the relationship between words.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        <span class="example">tavla</span>
        <b>X</b> talks/speaks to <b>X</b> about subject <b>X</b> in language <b>X</b>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        <span><b>mi</b></span>
        <span>tavla</span>
        <span><b>do</b></span>
        <span><b>lo badna</b></span>
        <span><b>lo jbobau</b></span>
        <small class="translation">
          <b>I</b> talk to <b>you</b> about <b>bananas</b> in <b>lojban</b>
        </small>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <p>
  Lojban uses words instead of special characters like quotation marks, parenthesis, exclemation points, and emoticons.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <p>
      lu coi li'u
      <small class="translation">"Hello"</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      viska to je tirna toi
      <small class="translation">See (and hear)</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      xirma .ui
      <small class="translation">Horses! <em>😊</em></small>
    </p>
  </div>
  <p>
    The order in lojban is not set it stone. It's possible to say the same thing in multiple ways.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <p>
      mi klama zo'e zo'e lo .gugdeburu.</br>
      mi klama fi lo .gugdeburu.</br>
      <small class="translation">I came via Brazil.</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      ko kurji ko</br>
      ko ko kurji
      <small class="translation">Take care of yourself.</small>
    </p>
    <p>
      mi nelci do</br>
      do se nelci mi
      <small class="translation">I like you.</small>
    </p>
  </div>
  <p>
    Lojban is parsable by machine grammar, and has the strong potential for use on computer interfaces and as a programming language. Artificial intelligence researchers have suggested using Lojban in AI development.
  </p>
  <div class="examples">
    <div class="line">
      <p>
        mi tavla lo skami fo lo jbobau</br>
        <small class="translation">I talk to the computer in lojban.</small>
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="line">
      <p>
      <span class="monospace">
        ([BH KOhA:<b>mi</b> CU] [BT{G:<b>tavla</b> &lt;LE:<b>lo</b> G:<b>skami</b> KU&gt; &lt;FA:<b>fo</b> (¹LE:<b>lo</b> L:<b>jbobau</b> KU¹)&gt;} VAU])
      </span>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
  Lojban is still an evolving language. The Lojban community has <a href="http://alis.lojban.org">translated Alice in Wonderland into Lojban</a> and created <a href="https://djemynai.bandcamp.com/album/zao">a Lojban rap album</a>. For more information, visit <a href="http://lojban.org">lojban.org</a>.
  </p>
  <h2>
    co'o
    <small class="translation">See you!</small>
  </h2>
</div>
